      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Version-controlled FEA solver with documented regression test suite; all analysis files stored in traceable repository with change history.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 used under an FDA-validated software configuration. Version control via Git with tagged release; regression tests cover linear-static and nonlinear contact benchmarks. SQA plan documented and reviewed by independent QA engineer. Achieved level meets required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA solver verified against NAFEMS benchmarks LE1 and LE10; results within 1% of analytical solutions.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical verified against NAFEMS linear elastic benchmarks LE1 (plate with circular hole) and LE10 (thick plate pressure). Computed stresses within 0.6% of reference solutions. Nonlinear contact patch test also passed. Code verification is adequate for the structural mechanics COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change <2% between successive refinements; GCI reported.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed on the screw-rod-vertebral body assembly. Stiffness QoI changed 1.4% from medium to fine mesh; GCI estimated at 1.8%. Final mesh (fine, ~420k elements, hex-dominant with tetrahedral fill at complex geometry) selected. Discretization error is well-controlled."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Newton-Raphson residual norm <1e-4 at each converged increment; energy criterion also monitored.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear quasi-static solution employed incremental loading with arc-length control near yield. Force and displacement residuals converged to <5e-5 at each increment. No spurious bifurcations detected. Solver error is negligible relative to model uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent analyst review of model setup; boundary conditions, loading, and material assignments verified against documented protocol.",
      "rationale": "Model setup independently reviewed by a second FEA analyst not involved in primary model construction. Boundary conditions (pin-pin ASTM F1717 fixture representation), applied displacement ramp, and Ti-6Al-4V bilinear isotropic hardening material properties verified against the analysis protocol. No use errors identified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Constitutive model (bilinear isotropic hardening) justified by uniaxial coupon data; contact formulation validated against analytical slip solutions.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening for Ti-6Al-4V calibrated against manufacturer-supplied uniaxial tensile coupon data (n=5 coupons, R²=0.997). Augmented Lagrange contact between screw and rod verified against Hertzian contact analytical solution (error <3%). Model form is appropriate for the compression-bending regime of interest."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from lot-specific coupon testing; geometric inputs from CMM measurements of production screws; uncertainty propagated via Monte Carlo (n=1000).",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus (114 GPa ± 3%), yield strength (880 MPa ± 4%), and tangent modulus derived from five coupon tests per lot. Screw geometry from CMM measurements of 11 production specimens (thread pitch, minor diameter, head geometry). Monte Carlo uncertainty propagation (n=1000 samples) confirms QoI sensitivity is dominated by yield strength; total input uncertainty contributes ±4.1% to stiffness prediction."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation specimens from production lot; N≥10 constructs; dimensional inspection confirms conformance to design intent.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs assembled from production-lot components. Dimensional inspection (CMM) confirmed all critical dimensions within drawing tolerances. Specimens distributed across two independent test laboratories to assess inter-laboratory variability. Sample representativeness is adequate."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios including at least two distinct offset distances per ASTM F1717; environmental conditions (temperature, humidity) documented and controlled.",
      "rationale": "Testing conducted at a single ASTM F1717 offset distance (44 mm) representing the worst-case clinical configuration identified in the risk analysis. While this represents the most conservative loading scenario, only one offset distance was evaluated; the required level calls for at least two distinct offset conditions to bound the loading space. Temperature and humidity were documented and controlled (23±2°C, 50±5% RH) at both laboratories. The single test condition represents a shortfall relative to the required credibility level for this factor."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA boundary conditions and geometry match experimental fixture configuration within measurement uncertainty; fixture compliance characterised and incorporated.",
      "rationale": "ASTM F1717 fixture geometry replicated in FEA from CAD drawings of the test fixtures used at both laboratories. Pin diameter and clearance measured and matched. Fixture compliance measured via load-cell and displacement transducer calibration runs; compliance correction applied to experimental displacement data before comparison. Equivalency is well established."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval) computed for each QoI; pass/fail against pre-specified bounds documented prior to unblinding of experimental data.",
      "rationale": "Acceptance criteria (E/uval < 1.96, percent difference < 10%) pre-specified in the validation plan and locked before experimental data were unblinded. E/uval computed per ASME V&V 40 Section 5 methodology incorporating model uncertainty and experimental measurement uncertainty. All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) passed. Statistical comparison is rigorous and pre-specified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) directly linked to clinical failure modes identified in the device risk analysis.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness governs load sharing with the spine; yield force determines onset of permanent deformation; force at 40 mm displacement characterises post-yield ductility relevant to fatigue initiation. All three QoIs are explicitly referenced in the device risk analysis (FMEA) as predictors of clinical failure modes. Relevance is fully established."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario (ASTM F1717 compression-bending) is the same loading mode as the COU; device geometry and material in validation match the submission device.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity uses the identical non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design, same titanium alloy, same ASTM F1717 test protocol, and same FEA modelling approach as will be applied in the COU. No extrapolation of geometry, material, or loading mode is required. Relevance of validation to COU is high."
    }
